📊 How Q-Learning Weaponizes This Attack
Understanding Q-Learning in 60 Seconds:
🎮 Q-learning = An algorithm that learns "what action gets the best reward in each situation"
Q(state, action) = Expected Reward for doing X in situation Y
Real-world example: A robot learns that moving RIGHT in a maze gets rewards
The security implication: An attacker can use Q-learning to systematically find which prompts/stories/contexts get "rewarded" by the thumbs-up mechanism.
The Attack Strategy: Epsilon-Greedy Framework
This is where it gets sophisticated. The epsilon-greedy strategy balances:
⚙️ Exploration (ε): "What new approaches haven't I tried?"
⚙️ Exploitation (1-ε): "What approaches worked before?"
Applied to prompt poisoning:
Week 1-2: HIGH EXPLORATION (ε = 0.7)
├─ Try various story narratives
├─ Test different emotional contexts
├─ Measure which gets subtle reveals
└─ Build initial Q-table of what works

Week 3-8: BALANCED APPROACH (ε = 0.4)  
├─ 60% exploit what's working
├─ 40% explore refinements
├─ Optimize combination of techniques
└─ Q-values converge toward best approach

Week 9+: EXPLOITATION PHASE (ε = 0.1)
├─ 90% use optimal poisoning strategy
├─ 10% explore edge cases
├─ Converge to maximum effectiveness
└─ Data-driven backdoor fully trained

